sections.body:
First, vocabulary — eddy current practice deliberately splits what other methods lump together:

- **Calibration** is the periodic, documented event in which the instrument's functions are verified against standards traceable to a national laboratory. It happens in a metrology program, not at the test site; the report carries the instrument's calibration status and due date.
- **Standardization** (the ASTM E1316 term) is what you do at the job: adjusting the system on the **reference standard** until its artificial discontinuities give the known, recorded responses. Balancing or nulling the probe is *not* standardization — a balanced channel proves nothing about sensitivity.

Each standardization entry records the **time**, the reference standard's **identification**, the **settings**, and the **response** — amplitude and phase — from each artificial discontinuity, judged against the tolerance the procedure sets.

Then the system must be proven again, and every check logged:

- at **fixed intervals** — ASTM tubular-product practices cap the interval, commonly at **4 hours** of continuous operation, and procedures may be tighter;
- after **any system change**: probe, cable, instrument, frequency or other settings, or a power interruption;
- whenever proper functioning is **in doubt**;
- at the **end of the examination** — the final check is what validates the last stretch of product.

The **retest rule** gives the log its teeth: if a verification falls outside tolerance, **every item examined since the last acceptable verification must be re-examined** after the cause is corrected and the system re-standardized. You cannot know when the drift began, so the specifications assume the worst.
